{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.08,0.59,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4965"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman is brought to the emergency room in a restless and disoriented condition by her office coworkers. According to a colleague, she started having a severe headache followed by two episodes of vomiting during some project work discussion, which got worse within a few minutes, and she could not even call her colleagues with the correct names for help. She quit smoking when she was diagnosed with hypertension a few months ago and is not under any other medication except for her antihypertensives. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination she is afebrile and her blood pressure is 190/100 mmHg. She is not able to converse properly, her ocular movement and vision seem normal, but there is right-sided upper and lower limb weakness, the line-bisection test is impaired and there is the presence of nuchal rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of pathology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior communicating artery","Posterior communicating artery","Middle cerebral artery","Internal Carotid artery","Posterior cerebral artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESudden onset severe headache (thunderclap headaches) with common associated symptoms like brief loss of consciousness, confusion, vomiting, and clinical finding like neck pain or stiffness suggests a diagnosis of subarachnoid haemorrhage. Rupture of a berry aneurysm is the most common cause of subarachnoid haemorrhage. The major cerebral vessels and therefore aneurysms lie in the subarachnoid space hence rupture of such aneurysms leads to subarachnoid hemorrhage. The mean age of aneurysmal rupture is in the range of 50 to 55 years. Approximately 85% of aneurysms occur in the anterior circulation, mostly on the circle of Willis. With no hard localising signs or symptoms all the above options for the position of the aneurysm are possible. However the speech difficulty points to the MCA as the most likely case. Cigarette smoking, hypertension, genetics, alcohol, the use of sympathomimetics, and estrogen deficiency are some of the associated risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal carotid artery aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E may compress the optic nerve or optic chiasm causes unilateral visual loss or bitemporal hemianopia. \u003Cstrong\u003EInternal carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E aneurysm may impinging upon the cavernous sinus causes ophthalmoplegia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral artery aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E, may have thick subarachnoid clots, or parenchymal haematomas which may present with combination of hemiparesis and aphasia or visuospatial neglect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsually \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior communicating aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E; also \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E and superior cerebellar artery aneurysms may present with third nerve palsy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Middle cerebral artery aneurysm, may have thick subarachnoid clots, or parenchymal hematomas, which may present with a combination of hemiparesis and aphasia or visuospatial neglect.","Approximately 85% of aneurysms occur in the anterior circulation, mostly on the circle of Willis"],"references":["Koutsothanasis GA, Sampath R. Berry Aneurysm. [Updated 2022 Sep 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557480/","American Association of Neurological Surgeons. Cerebral Aneurysm. 26 April 2024. AANS.org [Internet]. Accessed on 8 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.aans.org/patients/conditions-treatments/cerebral-aneurysm/","Perry JJ, Stiell IG, Sivilotti ML, Bullard MJ, Hohl CM, Sutherland J, \u00c9mond M, Worster A, Lee JS, Mackey D, Pauls M, Lesiuk H, Symington C, Wells GA. Clinical decision rules to rule out subarachnoid hemorrhage for acute headache. JAMA. 2013 Sep 25;310(12):1248-55. doi: 10.1001/jama.2013.278018. PMID: 24065011. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24065011/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-01T16:09:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-01T16:10:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4965"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112472"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/131"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Subarachnoid haemorrhage","synonyms":["SAH"],"description":null,"position":null,"cre